  "prompt": "What will be the expansion of (x+1) ^(1/x)?",
  "response": "The expression \\((x + 1)^{1/x}\\) can be expanded using the binomial theorem, but it's more useful to consider its behavior as \\(x\\) approaches \\(0\\) or other specific values.\n\n### Step-by-Step Approach:\n1. **Behavior as \\(x \\to 0\\):**\n   - Substitute \\(x = t\\) where \\(t \\to 0\\).\n   - The expression becomes \\((t + 1)^{1/t}\\).\n   - As \\(t \\to 0\\), \\((t + 1)^{1/t} \\to e\\), where \\(e\\) is Euler's number (\\(e \\approx 2.71828\\)).\n\n2. **Behavior for \\(x = 1\\):**\n   - Substitute \\(x = 1\\).\n   - The expression becomes \\((1 + 1)^{1/1} = 2\\).\n\n3. **Behavior for \\(x\\) approaching \\(\\infty\\) or \\(-\\infty\\):**\n   - If \\(x \\to \\infty\\), \\(x + 1 \\approx x\\), so \\((x + 1)^{1/x} \\approx x^{1/x}\\).\n   - The limit of \\(x^{1/x}\\) as \\(x \\to \\infty\\) is \\(1\\).\n   - If \\(x \\to -\\infty\\), the expression behaves differently and may involve complex numbers.\n\n### Exact Expansion:\nThe exact expansion can be derived using the binomial theorem, but it is generally not as straightforward as expanding \\((1 + 1/x)^x\\). Instead, focus on limits and approximations. Summary:\n\\[\n(x + 1)^{1/x} \\to e \\quad \\text{as} \\quad x \\to 0.\n\\]",
